<subSubSection id="3BE6651EF67D8D08FF139986FAC2FAEF" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="73433695F67D8D08FF139986FAC2FAEF" blockId="8.[151,1437,766,974]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
<emphasis id="4188EA87F67D8D08FF139986FEEEFA3B" bold="true" box="[151,284,766,793]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="B4FC4D16F67D8D08FEA79987FE61FA3B" authorityName="Sdzuy" authorityYear="1955" box="[291,403,767,793]" class="Trilobita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pilekiinae">Pilekiinae</taxonomicName>
has generally been conceived of as consisting of early, plesiomorphic species of 
<taxonomicName id="B4FC4D16F67D8D08FA9C9987FA6EFA3B" authorityName="Hawle and Corda" authorityYear="1847" box="[1304,1436,767,793]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheiruridae</taxonomicName>
which lack the synapomorphies of other subfamilies. Lane, for example (1971, text-figs 10, 12, 13) depicted the taxon on his evolutionary tree diagrams as a basal Tremadocian bar from which other lineages were multiply derived. As such it has been considered a paraphyletic group. There is as yet little insight into its phylogenetic structure, nor that of the family in general. 
<taxonomicName id="B4FC4D16F67D8D08FE5E98F7FDB8FA8B" authorityName="Sdzuy" authorityYear="1955" box="[474,586,911,937]" class="Trilobita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pilekiinae">Pilekiinae</taxonomicName>
is used here for convenience, with the understanding that as more Tremadocian (and possibly late Cambrian) taxa are revised and described its phylogeny can be formally explored.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
